article.headline: Whalen scores 24 points in second half
article.linkText: Whalen's huge game carries Minnesota over Dayton
article.story:
DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- With her team ranked in the Top 10 for the
first time, Lindsay Whalen wasn't about to let Minnesota lose to
Dayton.

	   Whalen had 33 points, 11 assists, six rebounds and six steals as
Minnesota (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 10 AP) remained undefeated with an 83-64 victory Monday
night over Dayton.

	   Whalen was 12-for-21 from the field and 8-for-8 from the
free-throw line for the Golden Gophers (11-0).

	   "Lindsay Whalen is quite a player," Flyers coach Jaci Clark
said. "She made some tough shots with some people hanging on
her."

	   After a sloppy first half in which the two teams combined for 30
turnovers, Minnesota took a 36-34 lead.

	   Whalen said she wasn't looking to score in the first half.

	   "My teammates were getting a lot of good looks in the first
half and I concentrated on getting the ball to them," she said.
"In the second half, I hit some shots and starting making some
contributions in the scoring column."

	   In the second half, Whalen took over. She scored 24 points and
led the way when Minnesota broke the game open.

	   After the Flyers (7-3) cut the lead to 53-46 with 12:59 to play
on a 3-pointer by Chrissy Donovan, the Gophers went on a 15-4 run
over the next 6 minutes to take a 68-50 lead. After Kim Prince hit
a jumper, Whalen had back-to-back steals she turned into layups,
another layup and a 3-pointer to score nine points in just under 2
minutes.

	   "Lindsay turned the game around and put an exclamation on it,"
Gophers coach Pam Borton said. "She got that look in her eyes and
just took over."

	   Cyndi Stull scored on a drive to the basket to tie it at 39 with
about 18 minutes to play. The Gophers responded with a 14-2 run,
with Lindsay Lieser scoring six points.

	   Lieser added 12 points for the Gophers and Kim Prince had 11.
	   Donovan scored 19 points to lead Dayton (7-3). Stull had 13
points for the Flyers, and Stefanie Miller and Sarah Allen added 10
apiece.
